You are still married, and the Court still has equitable authority over whatever  Bob's interests are, right up until the date of divorce

Incorrect.  The Court has equitable authority to determine different dates for determining whether any property interest is marital depending on what constitutes "during the marriage" - that may lead a court to pick the date of the filing of the divorce as the end date, in some situations, or even a date prior to the filing or the wedding as the beginning date (i.e. when a couple purchases a home together before marrying) - but those are the exceptions to the presumptive rule

This is unfortunately a highly litigated area of domestic relations law, but the presumptions are all in our favor.  Bob would be the one who'd have the burden of proving that the date of divorce is not "equitable" for purposes of determining and dividing marital property

If you want to read up on the subject, I see a law firm in Cincy has done a thorough job of summarizing the main considerations: https://www.durstlawfirm.com/ohio-law-and-litigation-blog/all-about-divorce-in-ohio-propertyhtml

Length of cohabitation is not the same as length of marriage under the spousal support statute.  There's nothing magical about the 20-year mark other than that it is customarily a landmark after which our court will CONSIDER an award of indefinite spousal support as opposed to a finite number of years

A 25-year marriage or longer means our court is more likely than not to grant indefinite spousal support. Shorter than 25 years and it is not likely, however in your case we might still be able to get it, based on your health concerns and low income / earning capacity in recent years

Spousal support as the last piece of the puzzle in resolving a divorce and we're getting ahead of ourselves.  We can have this discussion after we have some idea of how to divide the marital property, and what income-producing assets could be allocated your way pre-retirement, such as the barberton rental

You're getting 10 steps ahead.  All those facts are true, and potentially relevant, but won't matter until we're structuring a settlement.  For example, your marital estate may be worth $1,000,000, hypotehtically, and Bob may own all of those assets (in property, or business interests, or whatever).  Therefore he may owe you $500,000 - the question will be how he will pay it to you - in installments, or all at once - and how to secure it... then after that is settled, we can consider how much spousal support should be awarded on top of all that, based on your respective incomes

As for taxes, the Court has a general rule: “The parties shall prepare their income tax return in the way most financially advantageous to both parties.”   This is because tax refunds, and tax debts, are marital.  And therefore, if you or Bob receive a tax refund during the pendency of a divorce case, you are supposed to escrow it with counsel, because it is a marital asset subject to equitable division.    (Typically parties then agree to just split any such refund, typically only a few $K, 50/50 ASAP, rather than wait around for the divorce to conclude.)  And therefore, however Bob chooses to file, whether separately, or jointly, the objective – from the Court’s perspective – is that you should do so in such as a way as to maximize the collective refund, or minimize the collective debt.  Some accountants use a Filing Status Optimization Report to compare/contrast what the outcome would be like if spouses were to file jointly versus separately.  That would require some level of cooperation with Bob to make sure the accountant has access to all of your respective tax information.
